INSERT INTO "articles_locales" VALUES('Why are habitats for pollinators shrinking?',NULL,'{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Green deserts are useless for wild bees","type":"text","version":1},{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"In agricultural areas, pesticides are one threat to wild bees. Highly toxic insecticides such as neonicotinoids can kill wild bees even in the smallest doses. Herbicides can be just as harmful. They destroy all the ‚Äúweeds‚Äù that serve as a food source for local wild bee populations. Another often overlooked problem is the increasingly intensive fertilization and more frequent mowing of meadows. These are increasingly dominated by a few grass species. This is because these grasses benefit most from the excessive supply of nutrients and displace flowering plants such as dandelions, cow parsley, buttercups, and daisies. The result is green, monotonous deserts that are useless for wild bees and many other insects.","type":"text","version":1},{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Less habitat in residential areas","type":"text","version":1},{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Even in residential areas, where many wild bee species have been able to escape, they are under pressure. Garden owners often spray various poisons, hoe and till away ‚Äúweeds,‚Äù and plant exotic plants such as hydrangeas, forsythias, and geraniums. However, their flowers are worthless to wild bees. Important microstructures such as dead wood, open patches of ground, and dry plant stems are considered ugly and untidy and are rigorously combated.","type":"text","version":1}],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"paragraph","version":1,"textFormat":0,"textStyle":""}],"direction":null,"format":"","indent":0,"type":"root","version":1}}',NULL,1,'en',1);
INSERT INTO "articles_locales" VALUES('Pourquoi les habitats des pollinisateurs r√©tr√©cissent-ils ?','""','{"root":{"children":[{"children":[{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"Les d√©serts verts sont inutiles pour les abeilles sauvages\nDans les zones agricoles, les pesticides constituent une menace pour les abeilles sauvages. Les insecticides hautement toxiques comme les n√©onicotino√Ødes peuvent tuer les abeilles sauvages m√™me √† de tr√®s faibles doses. Les herbicides peuvent √™tre tout aussi nocifs. Ils d√©truisent toutes les ¬´ mauvaises herbes ¬ª qui servent de source de nourriture pour les populations locales d''abeilles sauvages. Un autre probl√®me souvent n√©glig√© est la fertilisation de plus en plus intensive et la tonte plus fr√©quente des prairies. Celles-ci sont de plus en plus domin√©es par quelques esp√®ces de gramin√©es. En effet, ces gramin√©es profitent le plus de l''apport excessif de nutriments et d√©placent les plantes √† fleurs comme les pissenlits, les berces, les boutons d''or et les p√¢querettes. Le r√©sultat est des d√©serts verts et monotones, inutiles pour les abeilles sauvages et de nombreux autres insectes.\nMoins d''habitat dans les zones r√©sidentielles\nM√™me dans les zones r√©sidentielles, o√π de nombreuses esp√®ces d''abeilles sauvages ont pu se r√©fugier, elles sont sous pression. Les propri√©taires de jardins pulv√©risent souvent divers poisons, sarclent et labourent les ¬´ mauvaises herbes ¬ª, et plantent des plantes exotiques comme les hortensias, les forsythias et les g√©raniums. Cependant, leurs fleurs sont sans valeur pour les abeilles sauvages. Les microstructures importantes comme le bois mort, les parcelles de sol nu et les tiges de plantes s√®ches sont consid√©r√©es comme laides et d√©sordonn√©es et sont rigoureusement combattues.","type":"text","version":1},{"type":"linebreak","version":1},{"detail":0,"format":0,"mode":"normal","style":"","text":"","type":"text","version":1},{"type":"linebreak",